\fs32\b 2. Product Vision\b0\par
\fs22 Dessert Store is a lightweight web app that lets users browse desserts, add them to a cart, adjust quantities, and confirm an order with a clear summary.\par
\par
\fs22 The goal is a fast, reliable, and accessible ordering flow with cart state that persists across page refreshes.\par
\par
\fs32\b 3. Product Backlog\b0\par
\fs22 Scales used:\par
\fs22 \u8226? Priority\u58? P0 (highest) \u8594? P2 (lower)\par
\fs22 \u8226? Estimation\u58? story points (SP) using relative sizing\par
\par
\fs26\b Backlog Items\b0\par
\par
\fs24\b 1) Add desserts to cart and increase quantity\b0\par
\fs22 Priority: P0\par
\fs22 Estimate: 3 SP\par
\fs22 User story: As a user, I can add a dessert to my cart and increase its quantity so I can order multiple portions.\par
\fs22 Acceptance criteria:\par
\fs22 \u8226? Clicking \u8220?Add to Cart\u8221? adds the item to the cart with quantity 1.\par
\fs22 \u8226? When quantity \u62? 0, the product card shows a stepper with \u8220?Increase\u8221? and \u8220?Decrease\u8221?.\par
\fs22 \u8226? Increasing quantity updates the cart count and totals.\par
\par
\fs24\b 2) Decrease quantity and remove at zero\b0\par
\fs22 Priority: P0\par
\fs22 Estimate: 3 SP\par
\fs22 User story: As a user, I can decrease quantity so I can correct my order.\par
\fs22 Acceptance criteria:\par
\fs22 \u8226? Clicking \u8220?Decrease quantity\u8221? reduces the quantity by 1.\par
\fs22 \u8226? If quantity becomes 0, the item disappears from the cart.\par
\fs22 \u8226? When the cart becomes empty, the empty-cart message is shown.\par
\par
\fs24\b 3) Remove an item from the cart\b0\par
\fs22 Priority: P0\par
\fs22 Estimate: 2 SP\par
\fs22 User story: As a user, I can remove an item completely so I can quickly discard something I don\u8217?t want.\par
\fs22 Acceptance criteria:\par
\fs22 \u8226? Clicking \u8220?Remove item\u8221? deletes the item from the cart.\par
\fs22 \u8226? Cart count and totals update immediately.\par
\par
\fs24\b 4) Confirm order and show order summary modal\b0\par
\fs22 Priority: P0\par
\fs22 Estimate: 3 SP\par
\fs22 User story: As a user, I can confirm my order so I can see a final summary before starting a new order.\par
\fs22 Acceptance criteria:\par
\fs22 \u8226? Clicking \u8220?Confirm Order\u8221? shows an \u8220?Order Confirmed\u8221? modal.\par
\fs22 \u8226? The modal lists each item, its quantity, and line total.\par
\fs22 \u8226? The modal shows the final order total.\par
\par
\fs24\b 5) Persist cart across refresh\b0\par
\fs22 Priority: P1\par
\fs22 Estimate: 2 SP\par
\fs22 User story: As a user, my cart is saved so I don\u8217?t lose it when I refresh the page.\par
\fs22 Acceptance criteria:\par
\fs22 \u8226? Cart loads initial state from localStorage key dessert_cart.\par
\fs22 \u8226? Updates write back to localStorage.\par
\par
\fs24\b 6) CI pipeline runs lint, tests, and build\b0\par
\fs22 Priority: P0\par
\fs22 Estimate: 2 SP\par
\fs22 User story: As a developer, I have CI so I can catch problems before merging/deploying.\par
\fs22 Acceptance criteria:\par
\fs22 \u8226? GitHub Actions runs on push and pull requests.\par
\fs22 \u8226? CI runs npm ci, npm run lint, npm test, and npm run build.\par
\fs22 \u8226? CI fails when lint or tests fail.\par
\par
\fs24\b 7) Basic monitoring/logging for key events\b0\par
\fs22 Priority: P1\par
\fs22 Estimate: 2 SP\par
\fs22 User story: As a developer, I can observe key actions/errors so I can troubleshoot issues faster.\par
\fs22 Acceptance criteria:\par
\fs22 \u8226? Key actions (add/remove/confirm/new order) produce structured logs.\par
\fs22 \u8226? Errors are captured via an error boundary and logged.\par
\par
\fs24\b 8) Evidence artifacts for sprint reviews and retrospectives\b0\par
\fs22 Priority: P0\par
\fs22 Estimate: 2 SP\par
\fs22 User story: As a student, I can present clear evidence so the assessor can verify my Agile \u38? DevOps practice.\par
\fs22 Acceptance criteria:\par
\fs22 \u8226? Sprint Review and Retrospective docs exist for Sprint 1 and Sprint 2.\par
\fs22 \u8226? CI/test evidence docs include links/placeholders for screenshots or logs.\par
\par
\fs32\b 4. Definition of Done (DoD)\b0\par
\fs22 A backlog item is considered \u8220?Done\u8221? only when:\par
\fs22 \u8226? Code implements the acceptance criteria.\par
\fs22 \u8226? TypeScript builds with npm run build.\par
\fs22 \u8226? Lint passes with npm run lint.\par
\fs22 \u8226? Automated tests exist (unit or integration as appropriate) and pass locally and in CI.\par
\fs22 \u8226? No new console errors in normal user flows.\par
\fs22 \u8226? Changes are committed with a clear message and small scope.\par
\fs22 \u8226? Relevant documentation is updated (plans/reviews).\par
\par
\fs32\b 5. Sprint 1 Plan\b0\par
\fs22 Sprint Goal: Deliver the first increment of reliable working software by validating core cart/order flows with automated tests and establishing a CI pipeline.\par
\par
\fs22 Selected Backlog Items (2\u8211?3 stories):\par
\fs22 1. CI pipeline runs lint, tests, and build (2 SP)\par
\fs22 2. Add desserts to cart and increase quantity (3 SP) \u8212? proven via integration test(s)\par
\fs22 3. Decrease quantity and remove at zero (3 SP) \u8212? proven via unit + integration test(s)\par
\par
\fs22 Total: 8 SP\par
\par
\fs22 Notes:\par
\fs22 \u8226? Primary deliverable is verified behavior + DevOps pipeline (not new UI).\par
\fs22 \u8226? Commit history should reflect incremental progress (setup \u8594? first tests \u8594? more tests \u8594? CI).\par
\par
